{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"54c7e78a-9a52-4b73-9ae9-197dd893c661","content":"In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance **per HTTP request**. In MAUI, there are no HTTP requests — the app is one long-running process. So `AddScoped` effectively behaves like `AddSingleton`, and your DbContext lives for the entire app lifetime.\n\n**Fixes:**\n\n1. **Use `AddTransient`** — gives a fresh DbContext each time one is injected:\n   ```csharp\n   builder.Services.AddTransient<MyDbContext>();\n   ```\n\n2. **Create manual scopes** via `IServiceScopeFactory` if you need shared state within a logical operation:\n   ```csharp\n   using var scope = scopeFactory.CreateScope();\n   var db = scope.ServiceProvider.GetRequiredService<MyDbContext>();\n   ```\n\n3. **Use `DbContextFactory`** (recommended by EF Core):\n   ```csharp\n   builder.Services.AddDbContextFactory<MyDbContext>();\n   ```\n   Then inject `IDbContextFactory<MyDbContext>` and call `CreateDbContext()` when needed.\n\nOption 3 is the EF Core team's recommended pattern for non-request-based apps like MAUI, Blazor, and WPF.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3ca446e0-d60c-4063-ae20-649650ff9476","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a common pitfall when transitioning from ASP.NET Core to .NET MAUI regarding dependency injection scoping. This is a conceptual question I can answer directly without needing to search any codebase.\n\nThe key issue: In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance per HTTP request. In MAUI, there's no concept of an \"HTTP request\" scope — the app is a single long-running process. So `AddScoped` effectively behaves like `AddSingleton`, meaning the same DbContext instance lives for the entire app lifetime.","outputTokens":443},"id":"be769976-c2d1-424b-8cf3-ce8f6c188ab7","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:43:59.950Z","parentId":"00faa4da-7f59-4900-bbb5-e225e9a9568e"}
